Response to
Episode 1 - "Standing Up in the Milky Way"
@-------------------------------------------------
- Before watching this, I had never learned about the Oort cloud enclosing our solar system. I was surprised to discover that all this time there existed a shell of comets, held together by the gravitational pull of the Sun, around us. 
- In addition to that, there is so much to our world that I was previously unaware of. It’s remarkable how most of our universe appears invisible to our naked eye, but technology implementing infrared radiation allows us to visualize entire planets (like rogue planets). 
- This episode made me feel very small and insignificant (in a calming way). Our existences don’t matter in the grand scheme of things. Our galaxy, the Milky Way, has an entire other galaxy right next to it (Andromeda). In our observable universe, there exists a hundred billion galaxies. And all this is just a bubble in the multiverse! All of the things I stress about on a daily basis (grades, college, etc.) don’t really matter in the grand scheme of things. 
- Words have a lot more power and are capable of making a huge impact on the world even though we might not actively think that. By reading Lucretius’ work, Giordano Bruno was able to conjure up and spread numerous cosmological theories. Lucretius used a metaphor regarding shooting an arrow out into space and if it hits no boundary, then the universe is infinite. This led him to have a dream about a world enclosed in a dome of stars; however, he conquered his fear of the unknown and decided to look past this, discovering that his set of stars was just a few among many other galaxies’. Bruno soon after had an epiphany and connected this to how the power of his God was infinite, therefore the universe had to be infinite. 
- I really liked this quote by Bruno: “The revelation of this immensity was like falling in love"
- Bruno was a rebel. In his world, the Earth was still the center of the universe, and science was not allowed to go against religion. Despite being ridiculed after presenting his thoughts at Oxford, Bruno still pushed for his belief of an infinite universe. He was sentenced to 8 years of prison and torture, but still refused to go against his theories. At the end, he was burned alive for refusing to conform to the church’s beliefs. Years later, Galileo proved that Bruno was indeed right. This shows that you should never abandon your own intuition and vision for someone else’s. 
- Our entire existence was based on chance. Because of an unexpected collision after the Big Bang, our entire solar system formed. It’s remarkable how if the masses missed each other by just an inch, life as we know it would be nonexistent. 
